{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 09:23:43.575035", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network reachability snapshot\\n\\nScope and data used\\n- Source: reachability/ping sweep results collected across the lab (subset of hosts tested to limit runtime). The sweep includes pings from many endpoints (hosts and servers) toward two representative user hosts (10.1.4.16 and 10.1.3.17) and some server→host and DNS→host checks. I used the provided reachability output only.\\n\\nExecutive summary (top-level)\\n- Overall network connectivity is healthy. No packet loss was observed in the collected tests. OSPF-backed reachability between user subnets and the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) appears functional: web servers and the DNS server can ping user hosts, and many user hosts can ping each other.\\n- No persistent routing failure or device down condition was detected in the supplied reachability data.\\n- There are sporadic latency spikes on a small number of host-to-host test samples; these are isolated and not correlated across the network. No systemic congestion or loss pattern is visible from the current data.\\n\\nKey evidence / metrics\\n- Packet loss: 0.0% loss reported for all recorded ping pairs in the dataset.\\n- Round-trip time (rtt) summary across samples:\\n  - Typical rtt averages: ~1.1 ms — ~5 ms for the majority of pairs.\\n  - Observed rtt_avg extremes in the dataset: as low as ~1.10 ms, up to ~7.9 ms.\\n  - Individual sample max RTTs occasionally reached ~11–12 ms (single-sample maxima shown in ping outputs).\\n- Important endpoints present and reachable:\\n  - dns_server: 10.200.0.2 (reachable to other hosts).\\n  - web_server_0..3: 10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6 (reachable to user hosts).\\n  - Numerous user hosts in 10.1.x.x and 10.2.x.x ranges show two-way reachability to test targets.\\n\\nObserved anomalies (localized)\\n- No failure-level anomalies (no loss, no unreachable routes) in the collected dataset.\\n- Latency outliers:\\n  - A small number of host→host ping averages are elevated (examples in the dataset: rtt_avg values ~7 ms and single-packet maxima up to ~12 ms). These are not concentrated on a single source or destination — they are intermittent across different hosts.\\n  - Because the sweep used very small sample sizes (often 2 ping packets per pair in the provided results), the sample set is noisy; single-packet latency spikes can skew the average and max.\\n- IP addressing inconsistency (administrative anomaly):\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 is listed with IP 10.2.1.219 in the reachability output. This deviates from the typical host addressing pattern in your description (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 with hosts often in .2–.17). This looks like an out-of-range static IP assignment (not evidence of failure, but worth noting for inventory / addressing policy).\\n\\nRoot-cause analysis (what the data supports)\\n- Reachability and routing: Given zero packet loss and successful pings between servers, DNS and user hosts, OSPF appears converged and routing is functioning end-to-end for the tested prefixes (including the server farm 10.200.0.0/24). There is no data in the current sweep indicating misadvertised/missing routes or adjacency flaps.\\n- Intermittent latency spikes: The available evidence is insufficient to definitively ascribe a single root cause. Possible contributing causes consistent with the pattern:\\n  - Measurement sampling / noise: very small ping counts (2 ICMPs) make averages sensitive to single-sample jitter.\\n  - Host or hypervisor scheduling jitter on end-hosts or servers causing occasional delayed ICMP responses.\\n  - Brief interface queuing or microburst across one of the path devices (switch CPU/port queues), but not persistent since there is no loss and spikes are not concentrated on one path.\\n  - No signs point to OSPF route oscillation or link-down events as the cause (no loss, no consistent latency degradation).\\n- Administrative/configuration note: the out-of-pattern address (10.2.1.219) likely indicates a static IP or inventory mismatch rather than a network connectivity fault; this could cause future operational confusion but is not causing reachability problems today.\\n\\nConfidence and limitations\\n- Confidence in \"no loss / OSPF connectivity OK\" is high based on the collected reachability output.\\n- Limitations:\\n  - The sweep tested a subset of host-to-host pairs and used small ping counts per pair in many samples; this constrains the sensitivity to intermittent packet loss and transient routing events.\\n  - No traceroute, routing table (OSPF adjacency/routing table), FRR logs, or switch interface counters were collected here; such data would be required to pinpoint path-level causes of latency spikes or to confirm there are no occasional route changes.\\n\\nRecommended next diagnostic data to collect (for deeper root-cause isolation)\\n- Increase sampling and breadth:\\n  - Run traceroute (ICMP/TCP) from endpoints showing higher latency to the affected destinations to identify path hops where latency accumulates.\\n  - Re-run pings with higher count (e.g., 20–50 packets) and across more destinations to determine whether spikes are reproducible.\\n- Device-level checks (collect but do not act on them yet):\\n  - OSPF neighbor status and routing table (show ip ospf neighbor, show ip route) on core and distribution FRR routers to confirm stable adjacency and route installs.\\n  - Interface statistics (ifInErrors/ifOutErrors, drops, utilization) for involved router and switch ports along representative paths.\\n  - CPU/memory load on core routers and server host(s) at the times of observed spikes.\\n- Application-level checks:\\n  - DNS lookup and HTTP (curl) timing from representative user hosts to web servers to verify application-latency vs. ICMP-only behavior.\\n\\nBottom line\\n- The network is operational: no packet loss, servers and DNS are reachable from user hosts, and OSPF-based connectivity appears to be functioning. What remains are isolated latency anomalies visible in a small number of short-sample ping results; those are intermittent and insufficient to attribute to a specific networking fault from the provided data. Also, an addressing anomaly (10.2.1.219) was observed and should be noted for administrative review.\\n\\nIf you want, I can proceed to collect the additional diagnostic data listed above (traceroutes, extended ping runs, OSPF adjacency/routing tables, interface counters) to help localize any intermittent latency source and to verify routing stability., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='1e2fdf0a-ff05-4227-a3f6-c616e4ad3e22'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
